          "body": "The chapter's central pastoral turn comes in 4:17-20. Between the Kohath and Gershon assignments, God interrupts with a direct divine word: 'Do not let the tribe of the families of the Kohathites be cut off from among the Levites. But do this to them that they may live and not die when they approach the most holy objects' (4:18-19). The sequence is remarkable. God first states the threat (death), then immediately provides the remedy (Aaron assigns each man to his specific load). The protocol is not a gauntlet designed to catch Levites in a fatal mistake — it is a grace-structure designed to let them survive an otherwise unsurvivable encounter. The same logic governs the entire chapter. Israel's God is not looking for reasons to destroy His servants. He is providing the precise conditions under which finite human beings can carry infinite holiness through a finite world without being consumed by it. Order is not the enemy of grace; in Numbers 4, order is grace."
