        "excerpt": "This is the work of the descendants of Kohath in the tent of meeting, concerning the most holy things.",
        "body": "The Kohath section is the longest and most theologically loaded portion of the chapter, and its length is proportional to its danger. Kohath carries what no other Israelite touches — the ark of the covenant, the table of the bread of the Presence, the lampstand, the golden incense altar, and the bronze burnt-offering altar. These five objects constitute the entire cultic apparatus through which Israel's relationship with God was maintained. The ark is the throne of God's presence (Exodus 25:22); the table holds the bread that represents Israel's covenant meal before God; the lampstand provides light in the darkness of the Holy Place; the golden altar mediates the fragrance of intercession; the bronze altar absorbs the blood of Israel's sin. Kohath carries, in effect, the entire mechanism of Israel's access to God.\n\nThe assignment comes with an elaborate covering protocol (4:5-14) that the priests must complete before any Kohathite approaches. The sequence mirrors the spatial arrangement of the tabernacle: innermost first (ark, 4:5-6), then the objects of the Holy Place (table, 4:7-8; lampstand, 4:9-10; golden altar, 4:11-12; utensils, 4:12), then the outer court object (bronze altar, 4:13-14). The three-layer wrapping system — parokhet veil, tachash skin, blue or purple cloth — creates successive degrees of insulation between the holy object and common space. The blue outer cloth is the only surface Kohath sees. They carry what they cannot look at.\n\nThe embedded warning in 4:15 is the chapter's most urgent pastoral moment: 'They will not touch the holy objects and die.' This is not rhetorical hyperbole. The narrative of Uzzah (2 Samuel 6:6-7) and the Beth-shemesh incident (1 Samuel 6:19) demonstrate that unauthorized contact with the ark produces exactly what this verse threatens. The holiness of God is not merely an ethical quality — it is a power that destroys what approaches it improperly. Keil and Delitzsch (Commentary on the Old Testament) rightly note that these deaths are not arbitrary acts of divine cruelty but natural consequences of a finite creature encountering the infinite holy without mediating protection.\n\nThe divine interruption of 4:17-20 is equally significant. God addresses Moses and Aaron directly with a protective command: assign each Kohathite his specific object and load so that the whole clan is not 'cut off.' The phrase 'that they may live and not die' (4:19) reveals God's intent — the protocol is not a trap but a life-preserver. Aaron's task of individual assignment (4:19) is an act of priestly care: he stands between God's holiness and the Levites who would otherwise be destroyed by it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qodesh haqqodashim* (most holy things, 4:4) — literally 'holy of holies,' the same phrase used for the inner room of the tabernacle. Applying it to the portable furnishings asserts that these objects carry the holiness of the space they inhabit. *Mut* (die, 4:15, 19, 20) appears three times in rapid succession — the triad is emphatic. *Bala* (for a moment, 4:20) — literally 'to swallow,' used adverbially for an instant; even a glance at the uncovered objects is fatal."
