        "excerpt": "The responsibility of Eleazar the son of Aaron the priest is the oil for the light and the fragrant incense and the continual grain offering and the anointing oil — the responsibility of all the tabernacle and of all that is in it.",
        "body": "Verse 16 is a single verse that carries enormous structural weight. Eleazar, the third son of Aaron and his successor (Numbers 20:28; Deuteronomy 10:6), is given oversight of all the tabernacle's consumable resources: the oil for the lampstand, the fragrant incense for the golden altar, the daily grain offering, and the anointing oil. These four items are the fuel and fragrance of Israel's daily worship. Without them, the lampstand goes dark, the intercession ceases, the daily offering fails, and the priestly consecration cannot be renewed.\n\nThe verse then expands Eleazar's scope to 'the responsibility of all the tabernacle and of all that is in it, with the sanctuary and its furnishings.' This is not merely a list of Eleazar's chores — it is a description of the priestly superintendency that stands above the Levitical clans. Aaron's eldest surviving son (Nadab and Abihu had been killed in Leviticus 10:1-2 for offering unauthorized fire) is the supervisory priest over the entire operation. Eleazar oversees Kohath's cargo; Ithamar (4:28, 33) oversees Gershon and Merari. The priestly chain of command runs: God → Moses → Aaron → Eleazar/Ithamar → Levitical clans.\n\nThe positioning of verse 16 between the Kohath assignment (4:1-15) and the divine warning about the Kohathites (4:17-20) is narratively intentional. Eleazar's appointment is the structural answer to the danger the Kohathites face. The consumables Eleazar guards are what keep the worship alive; his supervision is what keeps the Kohathites alive. Priestly oversight is not an organizational preference — it is a life-and-death requirement.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pequddah* (responsibility/oversight, used twice in 4:16) — from the same root as *paqad* (to number, appoint, attend to). Eleazar is not merely a supply clerk; he is the appointed guardian, the one who has been formally *paqad*-ed to these duties. The repetition of *pequddah* frames both his specific and his general oversight."
