        "body": "The Gershon and Merari sections follow the same structural template as the Kohath section but with important differences in detail that reveal the theological logic of the assignments. Gershon's cargo is the fabric envelope of the tabernacle — the curtains, screens, and hangings that defined the sacred perimeter (4:25-26). These textiles were the visual boundary between the realm of God and the surrounding camp. They were not intrinsically holy in the same grade as the inner furnishings, but they were indispensable: without them, the Holy Place and the court had no walls, and the concept of sacred space collapsed. Gershon carries the container.\n\nMerari's cargo is heavier and more mechanical: the structural framework of boards, crossbars, pillars, sockets, tent pegs, and cords (4:31-32). The tabernacle's structural integrity depended entirely on Merari. The boards that formed the walls, the sockets that anchored them, the bars that locked them together — without these, the curtains Gershon carried had nothing to hang on, and the furnishings Kohath carried had no room to inhabit. Merari carries the bones of the building.\n\nTwo details in the Merari assignment deserve particular attention. First, 4:32 specifies that each man is assigned his load 'by name' — individual accountability for specific structural pieces. In a large clan carrying dozens of identical-looking sockets and bars, named accountability prevented confusion, loss, and the negligent arrival at the next campsite missing a critical structural component. Second, both Gershon and Merari serve under Ithamar (4:28, 33), Aaron's surviving younger son. The distribution of priestly supervision — Eleazar over Kohath, Ithamar over Gershon and Merari — mirrors the hierarchy of the cargo itself.\n\nThe principle embedded in these assignments reaches into the New Testament's theology of spiritual gifts. Paul's description of the body in 1 Corinthians 12:22-24 — 'the members of the body which seem to be weaker are necessary' — echoes Numbers 4's insistence that the tent-peg carriers and curtain haulers are as numbered and named as the ark-carriers. God's economy of service has no genuinely menial roles; it has only assigned ones.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Massa* (load, burden, 4:24, 27, 31, 32) carries in Hebrew both the physical sense of a weight to be carried and the broader sense of an appointed responsibility. The same word is used for prophetic 'burdens' (Isaiah 13:1; Nahum 1:1). Gershon's and Merari's assigned loads are their massa in both senses — literal cargo and divinely appointed accountability."
